com.noctarius.snowcast

Class SnowcastSequenceUtils

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.noctarius.snowcast.SnowcastSequenceUtils

  • @ThreadSafe
public final class SnowcastSequenceUtils
extends Object
    This class contains a collection of helper methods to easy the use of snowcast. It provides the user with functionality to extract timestamp-, counter-value and logicalNodeId from a sequence id and to compare sequence ids without the need for boxing/unboxing as the SnowcastTimestampComparator would have to.

        Returns:

      • timestampValue

        @Nonnegative
public static long timestampValue(long sequenceId)
        This helper method extracts the timestamp value from a given sequence id. This timestamp value can be used to order multiple sequence ids depending on their generation time.
        To compare timestamps and order sequence ids accordingly please find compareTimestamp(long, long) as well as SnowcastTimestampComparator.
        Parameters:
        sequenceId - the sequence id to extract the timestamp value from
        Returns:
        the extracted timestamp value based on the generation epoch

      • logicalNodeId

        @Nonnegative
public static int logicalNodeId(long sequenceId)

        This helper method extracts the logicalNodeId from a given sequence id. This logicalNodeId identifies the logical node at generation time. Since assignment is automatic and there is no guarantee that a node has always the same logicalNodeId users are not expected to make assumptions based on this id!.

        This overload always assumes a maximal node count of 8192 nodes. For a divergent number of maximum nodes at generation time of the sequenceId please use logicalNodeId(long, int) and specify the maximum node count.

        Parameters:
        sequenceId - the sequence id to extract the logicalNodeId value from
        Returns:
        the extracted logicalNodeId

        This helper method extracts the logicalNodeId from a given sequence id. This logicalNodeId identifies the logical node at generation time. Since assignment is automatic and there is no guarantee that a node has always the same logicalNodeId users are not expected to make assumptions based on this id!.

        Parameters:

        Throws:

      • counterValue

        @Nonnegative
public static int counterValue(long sequenceId)

        This helper method extracts the counter value from a given sequence id. This counter value identifies the order and count of generated sequence ids on a node in this ids timestamp value.

        This overload always assumes a maximal node count of 8192 nodes. For a divergent number of maximum nodes at generation time of the sequenceId please use counterValue(long, int) and specify the maximum node count.

        Parameters:
        sequenceId - the sequence id to extract the counter value from
        Returns:
        the extracted logicalNodeId

      • compareTimestamp

        public static int compareTimestamp(long sequenceId1,
                   long sequenceId2)
        This helper method provides a comparison implementation to order or compare two distinct sequence ids by their internal timestamp value. The counter value is not taken into account which might be enough depending on the application. This saves some CPU cycles to extract the second value.
        Parameters:
        sequenceId1 - the first sequence id to be compared
        sequenceId2 - the second sequence if to be compared
        Returns:
        a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as the first argument is less than, equal to, or greater than the second.

      • compareSequence

        public static int compareSequence(long sequenceId1,
                  long sequenceId2)

        This helper method provides a comparison implementation to order or compare two distinct sequence ids by their internal timestamp and counter value.

        This overload always assumes a maximal node count of 8192 nodes. For a divergent number of maximum nodes at generation time of the sequenceId please use compareSequence(long, long, int) and specify the maximum node count.

        Parameters:
        sequenceId1 - the first sequence id to be compared
        sequenceId2 - the second sequence if to be compared
        Returns:
        a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as the first argument is less than, equal to, or greater than the second.
